SCENARIO 1: You started work on wrong branch
❓ Situation:

You made changes on main instead of feature/login

✅ Fix:
# Save current changes
git stash

# Switch to correct branch
git checkout feature/login

# Apply changes
git stash pop
💡 Better way (cleaner approach):
git checkout -b feature/login

👉 This moves your current work into a new branch

Layman:
You wrote notes in the wrong notebook → move them to the correct one

🔥 SCENARIO 2: Undo last commit (but keep code)
❓ Situation:

You committed but forgot to add one file

✅ Fix:
git reset --soft HEAD~1

Then:

git add .
git commit -m "updated commit"

Layman:
Undo the “save”, but keep your work

🔥 SCENARIO 3: Undo last commit completely (danger)
git reset --hard HEAD~1

⚠️ Deletes code permanently

Layman:
Delete last step like it never happened

🔥 SCENARIO 4: Fix wrong commit message
git commit --amend -m "correct message"
🔥 SCENARIO 5: Push rejected (someone pushed before you)
❓ Error:
rejected: fetch first
✅ Fix:
git pull origin main --rebase
git push origin main

Layman:
Take latest updates → then add yours

🔥 SCENARIO 6: Resolve merge conflict
❓ Situation:

Two people changed same file

Steps:
git pull origin main

👉 Conflict appears

Open file:

<<<<<<< HEAD
your code
=======
other code
>>>>>>> branch
Fix:
Edit manually
Remove conflict markers

Then:

git add .
git commit -m "resolved conflict"
🔥 SCENARIO 7: Recover deleted branch
git reflog

Find commit ID

git checkout -b recovered-branch <commit_id>

Layman:
Git keeps hidden history → you can recover lost work

🔥 SCENARIO 8: Move one commit to another branch
git cherry-pick <commit_id>
🔥 SCENARIO 9: Temporarily save work (urgent switch)
git stash
git checkout main

Later:

git stash pop
🔥 SCENARIO 10: Remove file from Git but keep locally
git rm --cached file.txt
🔥 SCENARIO 11: Clean commit history (important for interviews)
git rebase -i HEAD~3

Options:

squash
edit
drop

👉 Used before PR

🔥 SCENARIO 12: Rollback production issue safely
git revert <commit_id>

👉 Creates new commit (safe for teams)

DO NOT USE:

git reset --hard   ❌ (in shared repo)
🔥 SCENARIO 13: Clone specific branch only
git clone -b dev <repo_url>
🔥 SCENARIO 14: Check who changed what
git blame file.txt
🔥 SCENARIO 15: Find bug using commits
git bisect start
git bisect bad
git bisect good <commit_id>

👉 Git auto-finds bad commit

🔥 SCENARIO 16: Tag release version
git tag v1.0
git push origin v1.0
🔥 SCENARIO 17: Force push (DANGEROUS)
git push --force

👉 Only use if:

You know impact
No one else is working
🔥 SCENARIO 18: Sync forked repo
git remote add upstream <original_repo>
git fetch upstream
git merge upstream/main
🔥 SCENARIO 19: Ignore already committed file
git rm -r --cached .
git add .
git commit -m "apply gitignore"
🔥 SCENARIO 20: Large team workflow (real DevOps)
Flow:
git checkout -b feature/payment
git add .
git commit -m "feature added"
git push origin feature/payment

👉 Create PR → review → merge to develop → pipeline runs (e.g., Jenkins)
